<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12017d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12017d">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12017d"> 17(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Druids use Greek alphabet / for state papers (Caesar)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">C&eacute;sar dit &ldquo;qu&apos;ils <font color="green">[the druids]</font> &eacute;tudiaient les astres et leurs r&eacute;- <font color="green">[143]</font> volutions, l&apos;&eacute;tendue du monde et des terres, la nature des choses, la force et la puissance des dieux immortels&rdquo;. Il ajoute que, pour les affaires d&apos;&eacute;tat, ils se servaient de l&apos;alphabet grec; mais qu&apos;ils consid&eacute;raient comme un sacril&egrave;ge de confier leurs pr&eacute;ceptes &agrave; l&apos;&eacute;criture, ce qui implique n&eacute;cessairement l&apos;id&eacute;e d&apos;une doctrine secr&egrave;te. <br> <font color="green">[Caesar says that &ldquo;they [the druids]</font> studied the stars and their revolutions, the whole world and the earth, the nature of things, the power of the immortal gods&rdquo;. He adds that, for their political writings, they make use of Greek letters; but that they consider it a sacrilege to commit their secrets to writing, which seems to imply a secret doctrine.] <small> &Eacute;douard Schur&eacute;, <a name="ESLL" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ESLL"><cite title="source">Les Grandes L&eacute;gendes de France</cite></a> (1892) 143</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Julius Caesar&apos;s <cite>De Bello Gallico</cite>, VI.14: Neque fas esse existimant ea litteris mandare, cum in reliquis fere rebus, publicis privatisque rationibus, Graecis litteris utantur. <br>[And they [the Druids] do not think it proper to commit these utterances [sacred verse] to writing, although in almost all other matters, and in their public and private accounts, they make use of Greek letters.] </mm> </dd></dl>
